Yes. `OrderedDict.items()` will return the `items` in the order they are inserted.

If you check the [implementation](https://github.com/python/cpython/blob/master/Lib/collections/__init__.py#L81) of `OrderedDict`, you can see that `items` returns `_OrderedDictItemsView`.

    class OrderedDict(dict):
        ...
        ...
        def items(self):
            &quot;D.items() -&gt; a set-like object providing a view on D&#39;s items&quot;
            return _OrderedDictItemsView(self)

And if you dig deep and find the [implementation](https://github.com/python/cpython/blob/master/Lib/collections/__init__.py#L66) of `_OrderedDictItemsView`,

    class _OrderedDictItemsView(_collections_abc.ItemsView):
    
        def __reversed__(self):
            for key in reversed(self._mapping):
                yield (key, self._mapping[key])

And if you go deeper to check the [_collections_abc.ItemsView](https://github.com/python/cpython/blob/master/Lib/_collections_abc.py#L725), you will see that,

    class ItemsView(MappingView, Set):
        ...
        ...
        def __iter__(self):
            for key in self._mapping:
               yield (key, self._mapping[key])

And further down the [MappingView](https://github.com/python/cpython/blob/master/Lib/_collections_abc.py#L694), you will see,

    class MappingView(Sized):
    
        __slots__ = &#39;_mapping&#39;,
    
        def __init__(self, mapping):
            self._mapping = mapping

Now our journey has reached it&#39;s destination, and we can see that the `_mapping` is the `OrderedDict` we created and it is always in order. The `__iter__` method `ItemsView`, just iterates through each key value in the `OrderedDict`. Hence the proof :)

